<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 9:17<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If63c44816b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I4b277990933c11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>9.</label.designator><headtext>Effect of Transfer: Proceedings in the Transferee Court</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94f9b70fe1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>9:17.</label.designator><headtext>Management of transferred cases—Coordination with other litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Another frequent—and increasingly important—part of management of transferred cases is the coordination of those cases with other litigation. <eos/><bos/>This aspect of case management is implicit in the Panel&apos;s articulation of the opportunity to effect this coordination as a reason to order transfer[<footnote.reference refid="If63c44826b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>] or for slextion of a particular transferee district[<footnote.reference refid="If63c6b916b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>] or transferee judge.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If63c6b946b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Accomplishment of this goal requires numerous actions, and often cannot be simply done. <eos/><bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0304914122" w-serial-number="2010842348" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000344" ID="I7062fa716b3e11e9b53ce93f2bd0c1c1"><ital>In re Zyprexa Products Liability Litigation</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="If63c92a06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">4</footnote.reference>] Judge Jack Weinstein outlines the efforts taken to coordinate with related state court litigation, including:</paratext><list><list.item><para><head parent="para"><label.designator>•</label.designator></head><paratext>Sending federal MDL orders to the state judges</paratext></para></list.item><list.item><para><head parent="para"><label.designator>•</label.designator></head><paratext>Coordination with state court judges</paratext></para></list.item><list.item><para><head parent="para"><label.designator>•</label.designator></head><paratext>Sharing of information collected by plaintiffs&apos; counsel in federal case with state court plantiffs</paratext></para></list.item><list.item><para><head parent="para"><label.designator>•</label.designator></head><paratext>Urging the parties to cooperate in coordinating the cases</paratext></para></list.item><list.item><para><head parent="para"><label.designator>•</label.designator></head><paratext>Directions to settlement masters to obtain global settlements</paratext></para></list.item></list><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If63c44816b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If63c44826b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs5:25" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If63c6b906b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 5:25</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If63c6b916b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> §§ <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs6:12" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If63c6b926b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">6:12</cite.query> &amp;  <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs6:13" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If63c6b936b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">6:13</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If63c6b946b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs7:10" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If63c6b956b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 7:10</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If63c92a06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0304914122" w-serial-number="2010842348" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000344" w-pinpoint-page="541" ID="I706348916b3e11e9b53ce93f2bd0c1c1">In re Zyprexa Products Liability Litigation, 238 F.R.D. 539, 541 (E.D. N.Y. 2006)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royal